Instead of splitting, you can use a `Pattern` and `Matcher` to capture all the values which are immediately followed by a tab character, or the end of the sequence.

The regular expression pattern is as follows.

```regex
([^\t]*?)(?:\t|$)
```

Here is a method which will return a `List` of `String` values.

```java
List&lt;String&gt; split(String string) {
    List&lt;String&gt; split = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile(&quot;([^\\t]*?)(?:\\t|$)&quot;);
    Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(string);
    StringBuilder builder = new StringBuilder();
    String group;
    while (matcher.find()) {
        group = matcher.group(1);
        if (group.startsWith(&quot;\&quot;\&quot;&quot;)) {
            builder.append(group);
            if (group.endsWith(&quot;\&quot;\&quot;&quot;)) {
                split.add(builder.toString());
                builder = new StringBuilder();
            }
        } else if (group.startsWith(&quot;\&quot;&quot;) &amp;&amp; !group.endsWith(&quot;\&quot;\&quot;&quot;)) {
            if (!builder.isEmpty()) builder.append(&#39;\t&#39;).append(group);
            else split.add(group);
        } else if (group.endsWith(&quot;\&quot;\&quot;&quot;)) {
            builder.append(&#39;\t&#39;).append(group);
            split.add(builder.toString());
            builder = new StringBuilder();
        } else
            split.add(group);
    }
    return split;
}
```

